d` because it is not a server-managed memory session; I’ll keep that ID only in the review lineage state and rerun memory context without binding it.I found the lineage artifact directory already exists with only `.executor-state/`; phase initialization can create the review packet files there without overwriting prior review state.Code graph is stale, so I’ll avoid relying on structural graph answers for findings and use direct spec/code reads plus Grep/Glob evidence instead.The parent review config names a files-target review over launcher daemon supervision, hook portability configs, cleanup, and comment hygiene scripts. I’ll run this lineage as an independent one-iteration correctness-focused review and then synthesize within the `gpt55-2` artifact root.Phase initialization context is sufficient; I’m narrowing the single iteration to the recent daemon re-election/reap and hook portability paths because those are the highest-risk correctness surfaces in the target set.I haven’t found a high-confidence P0/P1 in the first pass yet. I’m checking the committed tests against the launcher paths now so any finding is grounded in code/test evidence rather than an inferred race.One high-confidence gap is emerging: the stale-owner reclaim path preserves single-writer safety by reaping the released daemon, but it has no adoption/active-secondary gate, so a third session can interrupt a secondary that survived owner disposal. I’m checking for additional smaller issues before writing the one-iteration state.The syntax checks passed for both launchers and the cleanup script, and the current hygiene checker exits clean on both launchers despite comments containing `096 packet` labels, so that smaller checker gap is also evidence-backed.I’m going to create the lineage-local r...\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/139-multi-model-deep/review/lineages/gpt55-1/iterations/iteration-1.md:\n  Line 1: Starting the requested deep-review lineage. I’ll load the workflow contract first, bind the artifact directory directly to the provided fanout override, and keep writes confined to that lineage directory.The memory trigger hook rejected the provided fanout session id because it is not a server-managed memory session; I’ll continue with the workflow session id as lineage metadata only and keep state in the requested artifact directory.Loading the review-loop references and the target packet inventory now, so the initialized state matches the skill’s artifact contract instead of guessing file names or dimensions.The lineage directory is effectively empty except for executor state, so I’m initializing a fresh lineage rather than resuming. Next I’m reading the spec packet and shared review context to select the single iteration focus and target files.The spec docs are still template placeholders; the actionable review scope comes from `review/shared-context.md` and the root review config, which list the actual daemon, hook, and test files under review.I’m focusing the single iteration on correctness and traceability of the daemon re-election/reap behavior, then checking hook portability for obvious regressions. That matches the high-risk surface in the shared context and root file target.A real issue is emerging around the stale-owner reclaim path: the code comment says the owner lease is an `O_EXCL` spawn mutex, but the stale-reclaim branch overwrites the existing lease with tmp+rename and then rereads it. I’m checking counterevidence before recording it as a finding.I’m writing the lineage state now. The findings will be evidence-cited and the iteration file will end with the exact required `Review verdict: CONDITIONAL` line because the pass has one active P1 and P2 advisories.The stale-reclaim mutex issue survived the counterevidence check: the bootstrap lock is not required when artifacts are already ready, `writeLeaseFile` has the same last-writer-wins/reprobe shap...\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/139-multi-model-deep/review/lineages/gpt55-2/resource-map.md:\n  Line 7: | F001 | `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1372-1383`; `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1482-1502`; `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/stress_test/durability/daemon-reelection-adoption-live.vitest.ts:193-207`; `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/stress_test/durability/daemon-reelection-adoption-live.vitest.ts:225-242` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/139-multi-model-deep/review/lineages/gpt55-2/iterations/iteration-001.md:\n  Line 5: Focus dimension: correctness. This lineage reviewed the daemon re-election/reap path, bridge/proxy interaction, hook portability files, session cleanup, and comment hygiene within the configured 12-file target set.\n\n  Line 18: ### F001 P1: Fresh session can reap a daemon still serving a live secondary\n\n  Line 20: [SOURCE: .opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1372] The release branch keeps the context-server daemon alive for adoption and only clears the owner lease. [SOURCE: .opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1482] A later fresh launcher sees the dead owner pid as `staleReclaimable`, reads `staleLease.childPid`, and calls `reapLeaseChildBeforeRespawn(orphanChildPid)` before spawning a replacement. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/stress_test/durability/daemon-reelection-adoption-live.vitest.ts:193] The tests prove a secondary can be bridged to that daemon after owner disposal, and [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/stress_test/durability/daemon-reelection-adoption-live.vitest.ts:225] separately prove a fresh session reaps the orphan, but there is no combined owner+secondary+fresh test.\n\n  Line 22: Scenario: session A owns daemon D, session B bridges to D, A exits and releases D, then session C starts. C reclaims the dead-owner lease and reaps D with no active-secondary/adopt-in-place gate. B's proxy may reattach to the replacement, but any in-flight request is dropped and the advertised \"secondary keeps transport\" behavior is no longer stable once another fresh session joins.\n\n  Line 28: [SOURCE: .opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:710] When the child does not exit after SIGTERM, `reapLeaseChildBeforeRespawn` sends SIGKILL and awaits `waitForPidExit(childPid, 1000)`. [SOURCE: .opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:726] The result is discarded and the function returns `allowed: true` regardless. If the child remains alive in an uninterruptible filesystem or WAL state, the launcher can spawn a replacement while the original daemon still holds the database.\n\n  Line 65:     \"title\": \"Fresh session can reap a daemon still serving a live secondary\",\n\n  Line 66:     \"detail\": \"The staleReclaimable branch reaps staleLease.childPid before respawn with no active-secondary/adopt-in-place gate. A secondary can be bridged to the released daemon after owner disposal, while the fresh-session test reaps the orphan only in a no-secondary setup. In the combined case, a third session can kill the daemon currently serving the secondary and drop in-flight work before the proxy reattaches.\",\n\n  Line 74:     \"detail\": \"After SIGKILL, reapLeaseChildBeforeRespawn awaits waitForPidExit(childPid, 1000) but ignores the result and returns allowed:true. A child that remains alive after the window can coexist with the replacement daemon on the same database.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/139-multi-model-deep/review/lineages/gpt55-2/deltas/iteration-001.json:\n  Line 24:       \"title\": \"Fresh session can reap a daemon still serving a live secondary\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/139-multi-model-deep/review/lineages/gpt55-2/review-report.md:\n  Line 5: Verdict: CONDITIONAL. This max-1 lineage found no P0s, one active P1, and two active P2s. The release/reap implementation preserves the single-writer invariant in the no-secondary fresh-session case, but the combined case of an active secondary plus a later fresh session can still disrupt the secondary by reaping the daemon it is using.\n\n  Line 9: Plan remediation for F001 before treating daemon re-election as fully release-ready across concurrent sessions. F002 and F003 can be bundled as follow-up hardening and tooling cleanup.\n\n  Line 15: | F001 | P1 | correctness | Fresh session can reap a daemon still serving a live secondary | `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1482` |\n\n  Line 23: | Released daemon adoption | F001 | In stale-owner reclaim, prefer adopting/bridging a responsive released daemon or gate reap on no active clients, rather than unconditionally killing `childPid`. Add a three-session test: owner + secondary, owner exits, fresh session starts, secondary request remains successful without dropped in-flight RPC. |\n\n\n(Results truncated: showing 100 of 168504 matches (168404 hidden). Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":168504,"truncated":true},"title":"daemon|portability|portable|pid|server|process\\.platform|platform","time":{"start":1780907765362,"end":1780907769350}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_001966feacef24af016a267ef52338819182e4d6bb70372f60"}},"id":"prt_ea65fee55001gH6gYZUibP13cU","sessionID":"ses_159a25826ffeGycQmqCQ1cpr4r","messageID":"msg_ea65fa941001VSfz2cV13PA54E"}}
