socket respawn branch: [747](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:747), [760-810](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:760). That branch is not reached for stale-owner reclaim.\n\n  Line 2057: **SEVERITY: medium-high.** SQLite WAL supports multiple processes, so this is not an immediate “two processes means corruption” finding. But two daemon writers against the same DB can cause lock contention, busy failures/timeouts, checkpoint starvation, WAL growth, and inconsistent higher-level daemon assumptions around single ownership. It is a regression versus pre-re-election behavior because the old shutdown path killed children and cleared leases at [1385-1417](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1385); cold restart would not overlap the old daemon.\n\n  Line 2070: The release path keeps the daemon alive and preserves the daemon lease: [mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1370](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1370) releases when re-election is enabled, [1377-1381] remove the exit cleanup, clear only the owner lease, then exit. The persisted lease records launcher `pid` plus daemon `childPid`: [model-server-supervision.cjs:705](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/lib/model-server-supervision.cjs:705) and [mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1307](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1307).\n\n  Line 2072: Fresh startup then classifies the lease by `lease.pid` only: [mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:554](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:554), especially `process.kill(lease.pid, 0)` at [562](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:562). If the owner pid is dead, it returns `staleReclaimable` at [565](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:565), ignoring live `childPid`. In `main()`, stale reclaim only logs at [1480-1482](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1480), then writes a new lease and launches a new daemon at [1502-1510](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1502). The existing child reap exists only in the dead-socket respawn branch: [747](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:747), [760-810](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:760). That branch is not reached for stale-owner reclaim.\n\n  Line 2074: **SEVERITY: medium-high.** SQLite WAL supports multiple processes, so this is not an immediate “two processes means corruption” finding. But two daemon writers against the same DB can cause lock contention, busy failures/timeouts, checkpoint starvation, WAL growth, and inconsistent higher-level daemon assumptions around single ownership. It is a regression versus pre-re-election behavior because the old shutdown path killed children and cleared leases at [1385-1417](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1385); cold restart would not overlap the old daemon.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/007-mcp-daemon-reliability/028-live-session-reelection-validation/scratch/council-brief.md:\n  Line 4: `/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public`\n\n  Line 48: cd /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/007-mcp-daemon-reliability/028-live-session-reelection-validation/scratch/reelect-doublewriter.cjs:\n  Line 12: const REPO = '/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public';\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/007-mcp-daemon-reliability/028-live-session-reelection-validation/scratch/reelect-holder.cjs:\n  Line 14: const REPO = '/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public';\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/007-mcp-daemon-reliability/028-live-session-reelection-validation/scratch/reelect-live-test.cjs:\n  Line 28: const REPO = '/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public';\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/137-deep-context-workflow-adoption/ai-council/council-report.md:\n  Line 93: - `/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/CLAUDE.md` (PRIMARY)\n\n  Line 94: - `/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/AGENTS.md` (PRIMARY mirror)\n\n  Line 95: - `/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-context/SKILL.md` (SECONDARY-B)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/134-deep-context-gathering/review/seats/seat-10.json:\n  Line 2: {\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"timestamp\":1780830073595,\"sessionID\":\"ses_15e41e4c8ffeCP0WGGT1eimWex\",\"part\":{\"type\":\"tool\",\"tool\":\"skill\",\"callID\":\"call_iPViYRU9JOCMZkQslCwhCSWL\",\"state\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"input\":{\"name\":\"deep-review\"},\"output\":\"<skill_content name=\\\"deep-review\\\">\\n# Skill: deep-review\\n\\n<!-- Note: Task is for the command executor (loop management); @deep-review agent is LEAF-only (no Task). No WebFetch: review is code-only. -->\\n\\n<!-- Keywords: deep-review, code-audit, iterative-review, review-loop, convergence-detection, externalized-state, fresh-context, review-agent, JSONL-state, severity-findings, P0-P1-P2, release-readiness, spec-alignment -->\\n\\n# Autonomous Deep Review Loop\\n\\nIterative code review and quality auditing protocol with fresh context per iteration, externalized state, convergence detection, and severity-weighted findings (P0/P1/P2).\\n\\nRuntime path resolution:\\n- OpenCode/Copilot runtime: `.opencode/agents/*.md`\\n- Claude runtime: `.claude/agents/*.md`\\n- Codex runtime: `.codex/agents/*.toml`\\n\\nConvergence threshold semantics and sibling-parity notes (deep-review 0.10 vs deep-research 0.05 vs deep-ai-council 0.20) live in `references/convergence/convergence.md` §1 under \\\"Threshold Semantics and Sibling Parity\\\".\\n\\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\\n\\n### When to Use This Skill\\n\\nUse this skill when:\\n- Code quality audit requiring multiple rounds across different review dimensions\\n- Spec folder validation requiring cross-reference checks between docs and implementation\\n- Release readiness check before shipping a feature or component\\n- Finding misalignments between spec documents and actual code\\n- Verifying cross-references across documentation, agents, commands, and code\\n- Iterative review where each dimension's findings inform subsequent dimensions\\n- Unattended or overnight audit sessions\\n\\n### When NOT to Use\\n\\n- Simple single-pass code review (use `sk-code-review` instead)\\n- Known issues that just need fixing (go directly to impleme...\n  Line 5: {\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"timestamp\":1780830091425,\"sessionID\":\"ses_15e41e4c8ffeCP0WGGT1eimWex\",\"part\":{\"type\":\"tool\",\"tool\":\"glob\",\"callID\":\"call_yU